the eccle&s;ia&s;tics re&s;umption of their property, mo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> of the abbey lands were given to courtiers, or fol<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"> to the gentry at an ea&s;y rate. In 1545, the parlia+ment complimented Henry with the chanteries, co<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">+leges, free chapels, ho&s;pitals, fraternities, and guilds with their manors and e&s;tates, together with 70 ma+nors and parks, which had belonged to the archbi+&s;hop of York, and 12 pertaining to his Lord&s;hip o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Canterbury.</P>
